<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Microsoft Windows 10 (B1607) Anniversary Update Clock?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=6521&amp;p=34702#p34702"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">grisha22 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />You can get old clock layout using the registry editor.<br /><br />Press Win+R and enter &quot;regedit&quot; and hit enter<br />Open the following key : <br />HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\ImmersiveShell<br />Click on the <strong>Immersiveshell</strong> folder on your left hand side. Following that, create a new <strong>DWORD (32-bit) Value</strong> in your right hand side. Name it <strong>UseWin32TrayClockExperience</strong>. By default, the value would be 0. You have to set the value to <strong>1</strong>. To change the value, double-click on UseWin32TrayClockExperience and enter <strong>1</strong> before saving your change.<br /></div><br />This tip is recycled in many posts that address the same issue, but somehow - following the guide(s) to the letter - it doesn't work for me. <br />I use Windows 10 Pro, winver reports [1607 (OS-version 14393.1358)].<br />What to do?<br />Thank you.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=14915">Kokopelli</a> — Wed Nov 15, 2017 5:20 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
